We are migrating to Open JDK11 a series of legacy projects. We faced a failsafe failure just by changing the JDK, without changes in the project POM or otherwise. Moving from 1.8.0_121 to 11 raised failsafe failure with &quot;NullPointerException&quot;:

    [ERROR] Failed to execute goal org.apache.maven.plugins:maven-failsafe-plugin:2.20.1:integration-test
    (default-cli) on project lib-mit8movimientosentretiendas-impl-local: Execution default-cli
    of goal org.apache.maven.plugins:maven-failsafe-plugin:2.20.1:integration-test failed.:
    NullPointerException -&gt; [Help 1]

Looking around we didn&#39;t see any indication pointing to a solution. We saw some comments about using newer versions (and not even the 3.0.0-M3, whose reports are compatible with JDK11, but as old a 2.22.0), or moving the plugin declaration from section `pluginManagement` to `plugins`... but neither helped.

Then we noticed that our declaration was specifying the provider manually with version 2.12 for JUnit 4.7.

                &lt;plugin&gt;
                    &lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.maven.plugins&lt;/groupId&gt;
                    &lt;artifactId&gt;maven-failsafe-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
                    &lt;version&gt;2.15&lt;/version&gt;
                    &lt;dependencies&gt;
                        &lt;dependency&gt;
                            &lt;groupId&gt;org.apache.maven.surefire&lt;/groupId&gt;
                            &lt;artifactId&gt;surefire-junit47&lt;/artifactId&gt;
                            &lt;version&gt;2.12&lt;/version&gt;
                        &lt;/dependency&gt;
                    &lt;/dependencies&gt;
                    &lt;executions&gt;
                        &lt;execution&gt;
                            &lt;goals&gt;
                                &lt;goal&gt;integration-test&lt;/goal&gt;
                                &lt;goal&gt;verify&lt;/goal&gt;
                            &lt;/goals&gt;
                        &lt;/execution&gt;
                    &lt;/executions&gt;
                &lt;/plugin&gt;

But not for the module that was now failing. We added the manual specification of the provider and it stopped failing.

